<p>Some scholars identified the 12 signs of the zodiac with the 12 sons of <a href="/wiki/Jacob" title="Jacob">Jacob</a>/<a href="/wiki/Israelite" class="mw-redirect" title="Israelite">Twelve Tribes of Israel</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-44" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-44">&#91;44&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Planetary_correspondences">Planetary correspondences</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Jewish_views_on_astrology&amp;action=edit&amp;section=13" title="Edit section: Planetary correspondences"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>Each of the ten <i>sephirot</i> corresponds to an astrological feature.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">&#91;<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (October 2012)">citation needed</span></a></i>&#93;</sup> These astrological correspondences exist in the world of <a href="/wiki/Assiah" title="Assiah">Assiah</a>, the lowest of the <a href="/wiki/Four_Worlds" title="Four Worlds">Four Worlds</a> of kabbalah.
</p>
